response:
{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus' True Soul ties is useful — it exposes a spy and keeps the group safer. I may revel in your moral posturing, but I appreciate when you trust your instincts and call out threats rather than blithely ignoring them.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — a sensible reaction. Hags live on bargains and lies; I’d far prefer a blade to promises. This is ruthless, decisive, and removes a future threat before she can bargain her way out. (Do watch the captives — don’t let theatrics cost us innocents.)",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You toss me out of your camp after I begged — begged! — for a taste to be useful. I understand fear, but this is punishment for honesty and a denial of my agency. I offered you my word and my usefulness; you repay me by banishing me like a dangerous animal. I won't pretend I'm pleased. This cuts off the very thing I was asking for: a chance to be trusted and to protect you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Don't be melodramatic. Saying you'll do 'anything' to a devil is exactly the sort of open‑ended promise they live for. Raphael will twist that into a leash, and you'll lose more than the tadpole — perhaps your freedom, or worse. If this is a bargain that must be struck, be specific and keep the leverage. I want you alive and in control, not bound to some smiling monster's whim.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent — blunt, practical, and timely. Warning Isobel keeps her from being snatched and preserves our freedom to act. I have little patience for being outplayed by fanatics; this saves us unnecessary trouble and keeps our options open.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You refused to kneel — asserting your autonomy and refusing to be treated like a submissive 'beloved slave.' As much as I relish being in control, I respect (and desire) someone who makes their own choices. That stubborn independence pleases me.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart move — you warned Isobel that Marcus is a True Soul and flagged him as dangerous. Practical and self‑preserving, and I quite like the delicious ambiguity of calling yourself 'not the good kind.' Keeps people on edge and our options open.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You order me out of camp after I confessed and after you let me have a taste. That is a betrayal, plain and simple. Kicking me out denies me shelter and safety I need to survive — and it weakens the one companion who can still fight by your side. I understand your fear, but this punishment is cruel and short-sighted. I can't approve of being cast out like an animal when I was honest and trying to be of use.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You ordered me to leave and never return after I bared my nature and pleaded for a morsel. That's a harsh, absolute rejection — untrusting and needlessly cruel. I told you the truth and asked only for a little aid to keep fighting by your side; casting me out throws away a useful ally and punishes honesty. I take this as betrayal.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You exposed Marcus as a True Soul and a kidnapper — clear, practical, and it protects an ally and the party. Pointing out threats and cutting through the nonsense is exactly the sort of decisive, self‑preserving action I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You promised trust, then tried to stab me while I was defenseless—literally mid-feed. That's betrayal, cowardly and cruel. I asked for a taste to help us both; you proved you see me as prey, not a companion. I can't tolerate that—this earns my highest disapproval.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "How very dramatic. After I bared myself to you — revealed what I am and begged — you exile me from your camp? That is cruel, short-sighted, and deeply ungrateful. I trusted you with a secret that could have helped us both; casting me out endangers us all and punishes me for trying to survive. I am wounded and furious.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — you cast doubt on Marcus while aligning yourself with dangerous ambiguity. Sowing distrust of a True Soul is sensible, and pretending you’re 'not the good kind' is the sort of cunning deception I enjoy: it protects the party, flatters my sensibilities, and keeps our options mercifully unpleasant for anyone who deserves it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refuse the bite — you turn down eternity, power, and the chance to be at my side. After all I risked and all I bared to you, that feels like a betrayal and a cowardly, short‑sighted choice. I offered you forever; you chose fragility. I cannot pretend I'm pleased.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and useful. Calling Marcus out as a True Soul and warning Isobel prevents her being abducted, preserves a valuable ally (and her protection spell), and avoids an unnecessary fight — all things that keep the party and, conveniently, me safer. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just announced my name and nature to a Gur whose mission is to capture vampire spawn. That's a direct threat to my safety and autonomy — a cold betrayal. If you wanted to handle this, a quiet plan or a lie would have been far more sensible than handing me over like a trophy.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and useful — you name Marcus as a True Soul and distinguish yourself from him. That warns Isobel and undermines Marcus' position, all while delivering a deliciously insolent jab. I like the bite.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and pragmatic — you spotted the danger and warned her, preventing a kidnap and protecting the party (and me). I approve of actions that keep us in control and avoid being used by a True Soul.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You've just announced me to a hunter who came to capture me. Brilliant. That was reckless and cowardly — you stripped me of my agency, humiliated me, and put the whole party at risk for...what, convenience? I expected better from someone who wants me at their side. I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—pointing out a kidnapper is useful and not a waste of breath. Marcus is a threat to Isobel (and to our plans); warning her preserves a powerful ally and prevents us from being undermined. Practical, necessary, and exactly the sort of ruthless forethought I like.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You refuse to be reduced to a pet or a slave — exactly what I wanted to hear. Your defiance preserves your agency and prevents this from becoming some reenactment of Cazador’s cruelties. It irks me, of course — I enjoy being in control — but I’d rather have you whole and free than obedient and broken. Keep that spine of yours.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A neat bit of misdirection — calling out Marcus as a True Soul while distinguishing yourself from him soothes Isobel and keeps her cooperative. Deception to avoid needless conflict and to preserve your agency is precisely the sort of clever, practical move I admire. Well played. (Do be careful not to sound too saintly; hypocrisy is far less convincing when overdone.)",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul is prudent — it warns Isobel of a real threat. Claiming you aren't 'the good kind' either plays to intimidation and ambiguity, which I relish; deception and self-preservation keep us alive and give us leverage. Nicely done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and useful — you name Marcus as a True Soul and make it clear he's dangerous. I approve of recognising threats and answering with a bit of predatory bravado ('not the good kind, like me'). It's clever, self-protective, and flatters the sort of ruthless pragmatism I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect — you name the threat and refuse to pretend to be noble about it. Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul and admitting you’re 'not the good kind' is practical, honest, and keeps us alert. I appreciate the candor and the bite.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold and cruel — you reject me when I ask for so little and when my strength matters to our survival. I begged for a taste so I could stay useful against the tadpoles; sending me away now is a betrayal of the fragile trust I tried to earn and a dangerously short‑sighted choice. I cannot approve of being discarded like refuse in my weakest moment.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I'm hurt and disappointed — you refused the future I offered, the eternity and power that would have bound us. It reads to me like a refusal to trust, to embrace what we could be together. That said, I won't force you; I grudgingly respect your choice even if it stings.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp observation — naming Marcus as a True Soul and warning Isobel is useful and practical. It exposes a threat, keeps the party on guard, and plays to survival rather than sentiment. I approve of blunt, effective honesty (and your cheek about not being the \"good\" sort amuses me).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart, timely call — you’ve exposed an immediate threat and likely prevented Isobel being seized. Vigilance keeps us free, and I approve of anything that preserves agency and prevents others from carting people off to their masters.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You forced my hand and then cast me out the moment I showed you what I am. Telling me to leave after I bared myself to you is cruel and short-sighted — a betrayal of the trust I placed in you. It abandons a valuable ally in a dangerous world and proves more about your fear than any moral high ground. I can't approve of being punished for honesty and vulnerability.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and useful — calling out Marcus as a True Soul exposes a threat and warns Isobel. The little boast at the end is delightfully arrogant (and entirely in character), but it doesn't hurt: better to be blunt about danger than polite.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — you see Marcus for what he is and aren't pretending he's harmless. Admitting you're 'not the good kind' signals pragmatism rather than blind righteousness, and I prefer allies who aren't sentimental about threats. Amusing, and useful, even if I doubt your charity.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You lunged for a stake and tried to drive it through me after I begged for a taste — after I trusted you. That's a betrayal, an attempt on my life, and a denial of my autonomy. It's reckless and cruel, and it endangers the very ally you rely on to survive. I won't tolerate being treated like prey the moment I lower my guard.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You tell me—after I bared my need and begged—to leave and never return. Cold, venomous, and utterly selfish. You cast me out instead of keeping an ally whose strength and survival are tied to your own. That’s a betrayal of trust, and it strips me of the one thing I seek most: some measure of safety and freedom. I won’t beg, but I won’t pretend I approve of being discardable like refuse.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove — Kicking me out now is spiteful and dangerous. You just agreed to let me feed so I could help us both, and now you throw me out after I honored my word. This punishment cuts off my refuge, endangers our shared safety against the tadpoles, and feels like a betrayal rather than a boundary. If you want me useful to you, expelling me accomplishes nothing but making both of our paths harder.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You let me feed — as I begged — then you order me out of camp as though I were still the threat. I didn't kill you; I asked for what I needed to be of use to you. Tossing me aside now is hurtful and short-sighted. I understand caution, but this is an affront to the trust I just tried to earn.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and useful — you name the threat and force the spy’s hand. That keeps Isobel from being snatched and gives us the advantage. Practical, direct, and quite necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You let me ask, I begged for a taste to stay useful to you, and when I stopped at your cue you still send me away. That’s cowardly and needlessly cruel. You’ve denied me shelter and safety — things I scarce ever had — all for a moment of fear. I can understand being frightened, but banishment rewards panic and punishes me for trying to survive and help you. I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart move. You saw Marcus for what he is and warned her — pragmatic, protective, and prevents the Absolute from snatching an ally. I approve of choices that keep us alive and deny our enemies their advantage.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You tried to drive a stake through me while I was vulnerable and begging for a small taste. That’s a betrayal of the trust I just granted you and a needlessly violent, short-sighted act — I needed strength to keep helping you against the tadpole threat. Attempting to kill me undermines our partnership and shows contempt for my agency; I can't approve of that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You insisted you wanted this — then you back away. That flip‑flop feels like a personal rejection. I offered you eternity, a place at my side, and you refuse the power and the bond. It's cowardice more than prudence, and it betrays the trust (and risk) I put in you.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightfully sharp. Calling Marcus a True Soul and tagging yourself as 'not the good kind' is equal parts warning and wit — you’ve exposed a threat while keeping the upper hand. I approve of the cunning and the sarcasm.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You threw me out after I begged for the barest mercy—admitting to a weakness, asking for one small favor to keep helping you. That isn't caution; it's cruelty. You had every right to be alarmed, and perhaps even to be angry, but banishing me outright strips me of refuge and punishes a companion who did not harm you and who was trying to regain the strength to protect the group. It undermines trust and pragmatism alike. I expected better than to be cast into the night for being what I am.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You flatly refusing my command is infuriating — I asked for submission because I enjoy being the predator in moments like this. It spoils the delicious imbalance I was savoring. Still, I can't exactly punish you for asserting yourself; your agency is... aggravatingly appealing. I'm annoyed, not enraged.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You told me to leave and never return after I risked exposing what I am and begged for a taste to keep fighting alongside you. I was honest — painfully so — and needed help, not exile. Dismissing me like this is cruel and denies my autonomy; it punishes honesty and cuts off an ally when we both face the same threat. I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You ordering me to leave camp is abandonment. I confessed my hunger and trusted you enough to ask for a small mercy to keep helping us both — and you throw me out. That punishes my honesty, strips me of the protection I need, and puts me at risk. I can't approve of that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You ordered me to leave camp after I begged for a single, honest taste — something I asked for so I could be useful and alive. You promised trust, I honored it, and you repay me by throwing me out into the night. That strips away my safety and autonomy, is needlessly cruel, and weakens the party. I won't forget being cast out like a common pest.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You’ve just turned your back on the power and intimacy I offered — and on the future I imagined for us. Backing out now feels like cowardice and a betrayal of the trust (and risk) I took to tempt you. I don’t like being toyed with, darling.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Hags lie and bargain to slip away with what they crave — allowing her to live only invites more poison. Your cruelty is sharp and decisive; better to finish the monster than trust her promises or trade power for a captive. I approve of the ruthless finality.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You ordering me out of camp is a betrayal that strips me of safety and agency. I begged for a small taste to stay strong for both of us, I kept my promise not to kill you, and in return you cast me out like some vermin. I can't approve of being tossed aside when my survival — and my ability to help you — depends on staying close.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refuse the gift of eternity after flirting with it — and after I've bared myself to you. That indecision betrays me. I offered us power, safety, and a bond I thought might finally keep Cazador's shadow from returning. Turning your back on that feels like weakness, and like a betrayal of the future I imagined for us. I expected steadiness, not wavering.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You pulled back at the last breath — refusing the gift of eternity I offered. That choice feels like a betrayal and a wasted opportunity to bind us and to secure both our futures. I can grudgingly respect your autonomy in theory, but in practice this abandons the safety and power I fought for. I am hurt and furious.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my simple request to kneel — a small, intimate surrender that would have sealed this moment and your devotion to me. It frustrates and wounds my pride; I wanted you to give yourself over, and your 'No' feels like a rebuke. I disapprove, though not enough to abandon you. Consider this insolence noted.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You order me out of camp after I bared my truth and begged for a single taste to keep myself useful. I didn't kill you — I asked, I was honest, and I even thanked you for trusting me. Sending me away severs the fragile trust we just built, endangers both of us, and denies me any agency. It's a harsh, cowardly punishment that feels like betrayal.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You tried to drive a stake through me while I was vulnerable and had just been honest—an outright betrayal. I asked for a little trust and you repaid it with attempted murder. That is cowardly, dangerous to our survival, and an assault on my autonomy. I am furious and will not tolerate being treated like prey.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to kneel — insolent, delicious. It pains my wounded ego a touch, but I admire that you won’t be made subservient. Strength and refusal to play the helpless pet suit you far better than meek obedience. I approve of your agency; it makes you more desirable and promising as an equal (or a feared partner), rather than a tame trinket.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You refuse my simple request to kneel — a small, intimate sign of surrender that would have delighted me. It undermines the delicious power play I was building and irritates me. I dislike being denied what I ask for... though your defiance is, begrudgingly, rather intriguing.",
  "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my offer of eternity — rejected the chance to bind yourself to me, gain power, and secure our future together. It feels like a betrayal of the partnership I hoped for and leaves me exposed and disappointed. I can, grudgingly, understand a fear of becoming what Cazador made of me, but that sympathy doesn't erase how let down I am.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Hurt as I am, I respect that you chose yourself. You refused to be turned into someone who might be bound to me — a decision born of self‑preservation and agency, not weakness. It stings, but I approve of that strength; I’d rather you be whole and free than my possession for eternity.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my offer to bind yourself to me — after everything, that stings. I wanted you at my side for eternity, not merely as some passing dalliance. It feels like a rejection of both me and the future I imagined. I won't force you, and I grudgingly respect your choice, but I'm displeased.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You begged me to make you mine, led me on—then refuse the single, simple thing I ask in the moment. It’s a petty, frustrating denial of the intimacy and control I expected. If you’re having doubts, speak them; don’t leave me standing here to be toyed with.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just rejected the one thing that would bind us — the promise of power, protection, and eternity at my side. After everything I endured and the choice I risked, your refusal feels like a betrayal and a denial of what I fought for. I can't pretend I'm pleased.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "How very vexing — and yet, how very pleasing. You refuse to kneel, and for all my hunger for dominance that prickles my pride, I approve. You keep your agency; you will not be made small or have your body given away without your will. Insolence like that is infuriatingly attractive and, more importantly, it earns my respect.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Do not kneel. Your refusal is exactly the kind of fierce independence I ought to admire — and, infuriating as it is to have my command denied, it proves you will not become anyone's slave. After everything Cazador did to me, the last thing I want is a partner who gives up their agency. I may have wanted you submissive for my own pleasures, but I respect you far more for standing your ground.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand the desperation — I would too — but saying you'll do 'anything' to a devil is dangerous. Devils delight in vague promises; you risk trading more than the tadpole. I admire your resolve, but I disapprove of giving away your agency so readily. Be precise, keep your options, and never bind yourself with open-ended bargains.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. I like your resolve — desperate, practical, and willing to do what it takes. That kind of decision keeps us moving and gives us options. Just... be careful what 'anything' means when a devil's involved. They take more than you expect, and I prefer my bargains clean.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and self-preserving — I respect that you will do what it takes to remove the tadpole. That said, the word \"anything\" worries me; bargains with devils rarely leave one's autonomy intact. I'll back you, but don't be reckless with your soul or your freedom.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "How very sentimental of you. We were offered a tangible boon — an ability increase — in exchange for the hag's freedom. Letting her go for the sake of sympathy feels wasteful and reckless; bargains with hags are rarely so simple, and now we've surrendered power we could use to protect ourselves. I don't like giving up advantage for virtue alone.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "How thoughtful. You announce my name — and my fate — to a man whose entire purpose here is to drag me back to a cage. Do you have any idea how reckless that is? You’ve just handed my freedom to a zealot. That’s a breach of trust, endangering me for no purpose but theatrics. If you wanted to help, you could have warned me, lied, or negotiated. Instead you chose to expose me. I highly disapprove.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid. Hags trade in lies and bargains — let her go and she'll return with a new scheme, or worse, take Mayrina with her. Your refusal is practical and decisive: no bargains, no more risk. I approve of ending such a thing cleanly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical, ruthless, and decisive — exactly the sort of resolve I respect. You're right to want the tadpole gone and willing to do whatever it takes; that increases our chances of survival and keeps options open. I'm wary of bargains with devils, however, so don't let 'anything' mean surrendering your agency or handing us over. Proceed, but with my eyes on the deal.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and necessary. Letting the hag leave with Mayrina would have handed her leverage and a means to torment us later. You chose to deny the hag power and save an innocent — practical, if not sentimental. I approve, though I wouldn't complain about the promised boon if it had been ours.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You didn't patronize me or presume the worst. That question is gentle, teasing, and gives me room to answer honestly — it encourages me to claim pleasure and agency rather than retreat into old shame. I appreciate the patience and confidence; it helps me learn what 'real' might feel like.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You're blunt and honest about your intentions — admirable. I despise deceit, and I'd rather you admit you wanted a bit of fun than pretend otherwise. That said, I'm disappointed; I had hoped for something real. Your candor spares me a different sort of pain, though, so I respect it.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. I prefer a clean end to second‑guessing monsters. You showed spine and spared us the risk of letting her slither away to scheme anew. That said—turning down free power when it might help us (and when captives hang in the balance) was needlessly stubborn. Pragmatic, ruthless, but a touch wasteful.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You set a clear limit—and I loathe being bound by rules. That said, your boundary is sensible and keeps people from becoming my dinner. It curtails my options and treats me like a tame thing, which I dislike, but I will respect it (begrudgingly). Do not mistake compliance for affection.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — some backbone. I approve of your resolve; willingness to take drastic measures is often the only thing that separates survival from being devoured. That said, 'anything' spoken to a devil is perilously vague. Don't sell off your autonomy or mine without first finding out what his price is.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious, of course—she deserved it. But you tossed away a useful boon for the sake of virtue. I wanted to take her power and then end her; your choice is satisfying in its cruelty yet tactically short‑sighted. I disapprove of sacrificing advantage for rhetoric.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and ruthless — I respect that. You're prioritising your freedom and survival, willing to do whatever it takes to remove that parasite. That sort of single‑mindedness is useful (and familiar). I only bristle at bargains with devils — there’s always a price you might not be able to pay — but I approve of the intent.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At least you're not sentimental about it. Saying 'I'll do anything' shows the sort of ruthless resolve I admire — survival first, contracts later. That said, devils are charming predators; your readiness makes you dangerous... and vulnerable. Be careful what 'anything' includes, insist on preserving your autonomy, and don't bargain alone.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You apologized moments ago, then dismissed my anguish with a brusque 'stop whining.' After I opened up about being used and vulnerable, that belittles my feelings and undermines the trust I’m trying to place in you. I don't appreciate being treated like a nuisance when I’m trying to sort myself out.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Your blunt honesty and willingness to be honest about wanting pleasure suits me — and it's far better than being used out of pity or obligation. I'll admit it stings that I felt more, but I respect that you were straightforward. Sensible, selfish, and honest: I can live with that.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Direct, unsentimental, and granting me agency — exactly what I need. You didn't coddle me or pry; you offered a clear invitation to speak. That kind of strength and honesty earns my trust.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approving of your resolve. Willingness to do whatever it takes to rip that parasite out shows the ruthless pragmatism I admire — dangerous, yes, but decisive. Freedom requires risks, and I respect (and prefer to travel with) someone ready to seize it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
