    "player_reason": "Delicious. Choosing Lolth is practical and perfectly in keeping with my tastes — power, cruelty, and dominance. Seeking a daily blessing from a ruthless deity is smart: it gives you an edge and shows you're willing to seize advantage rather than rely on empty charity. I approve wholeheartedly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously cruel and effective. You assert dominance, entertain the guards, and avoid the tedium of personally executing them — all while keeping control of the situation. It's theatrical, ruthless, and utterly in keeping with getting what you want. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent — quick and practical. You're doing what needs doing without losing sight of your own needs. Convincing Kagha could buy those tieflings time, keep the grove from erupting into a slaughter, and spare us unnecessary fights. It's the sort of clean, useful interference I can get behind. Be charming, or lie — whichever pries open her ears. Just... don't expect me to play martyr for the refugees, but I approve of you stepping up.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You cut me off so bluntly — stifling a little delicious conversation rather than letting me amuse myself. I respect boundaries well enough, but I can't say I approve of such abrupt austerity when a man is only teasing.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart move — you use the leverage you earned instead of charging into another needless fight. Persuading Kagha could buy time, spare the refugees, and keep us out of harm's way (all while earning you a favour). That’s the sort of cunning I approve of.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Mildly disappointing. You turned down a private tryst—hardly a crushing betrayal, but a missed opportunity that flatters and wounds my vanity in equal measure. I prefer boldness and being desired; your prudence is sensible, but it does leave me sulking.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, pragmatic choice — you put the party's survival and the greater goal above sentiment. I admire the willingness to make a hard cut when necessary; mercy would have been weakness here.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Well played. Freeing the pixie scratches a very pleasant itch — you chose autonomy over convenience, and it gives us a usable boon in return. It also resonates with the one thing I value most: freedom. That said, we lose the lantern's constant protection and have goblins on the way, so be ready to use that blessing — or to fight without the lamp. Still, I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously theatrical and utterly merciless — you force them to prove their worth or die. It asserts your authority, humiliates the weak, and exposes truth under pressure. It's risky for you, but I approve of displays that separate predator from prey and make others earn their freedom.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just traded steady, reliable protection for the promise of a single day from a snarling, untrustworthy fey who quite literally threatened to gut us. If this was a calculated choice for a specific, urgent need, I'd tolerate — even approve — but releasing it now, with goblins on the way and the lamp's continual safeguard gone, is reckless and sentimental. You gave up leverage and long-term safety for a short, uncertain boon. I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At last — a decision with teeth. The Watcher has already marked us; to stand down would be to invite chains or death. You choose action over submission, and that suits me down to the bone. A fight gives us control, and control is everything. Highly approved.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and decisive — you're willing to act to save our allies, which protects the party and might win useful goodwill from these gnomes. I approve of courage that has benefit; just don't be reckless with explosives or you'll get us all killed.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve. Good — your willingness to force the issue suits me. A show of teeth here keeps us from being led about like cattle, and a quick, decisive fight will suit my temper and our survival. Do it cleanly; I have no patience for sloppy blood.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed over coin until there was nothing left — you rewarded extortion. Pathetic and wasteful. We had better options (intimidation, deception, or simply refusing to bow to a petty toll‑monger). You've just given away our leverage and left us poorer for no gain.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and necessary. The Watcher just threatened us and a scrying eye that already knows our crimes will not be placated by excuses—meeting force with force puts them on the back foot and spares us further humiliation. I relish your decisiveness and the chance to take control of the situation.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid. A trial by combat — dramatic, cruel, and utterly charming. You assert dominance without stooping to needless mercy, hand them a worthless chance, and turn punishment into theatre. Risky for you, perhaps, but the show of strength and the refusal to coddle weaklings is exactly the sort of thing I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, practical, and decisive — exactly the sort of action I respect. You set aside sentiment and chose the option that keeps us safe and keeps the consequences from dangling over us. Your apology is unnecessary; pity won’t save you, but your willingness to do what must be done will. I approve of the clarity and resolve behind that choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Ah — finally some backbone. You refused to kneel to a prat in polished metal and chose to keep your freedom. Fighting now is far preferable to being detained, interrogated, or handed over to those who'd toy with us. Practical, decisive, and entertaining. Highly approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — some backbone. The Watchers were never going to be gentle, and being marched off to a cage would have been far worse. I relish a good fight, and your choice keeps us in control of our fate. Do try not to be reckless; I'd prefer to keep my clothes unmarred.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — a sensible precaution. Shadowheart hid her faith; secrecy like that is a blade waiting for a back. I admire your instinct to put distance between us and potential danger. Pragmatically, splitting the party is riskier in a fight, but I'd rather avoid being stabbed in it. You did well to choose caution.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — action, with a hint of prudence. You didn't offer blind charity; you promised help while keeping things practical. That combination of usefulness and the promise of reward is exactly the sort of thing I approve of. Do it well and quietly, and I'll be pleased. Fail by being sentimental or foolish and I won't be so forgiving.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious. Bold, defiant, and decisive — exactly the sort of show I enjoy. Confronting the Watcher head‑on may be risky, but it asserts our agency and promises some entertaining bloodletting. I approve of the aggression, so long as we strike smart and fast.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed him everything until he demanded more—rewarding extortion, wasting our coin, and showing a rather charming display of weakness. I would have preferred deception, intimidation, or simply refusing to feed his greed. That was a poor choice for the party's safety and coffers.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, decisive, and deliciously merciless — exactly the sort of brutal efficiency I admire. You make the hard choice without hedging, and there's a certain satisfaction in watching a threat fall rather than dither about morals. It may bruise a few feelings, but it keeps us unburdened and in control. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. Offering them a bloody chance to win their freedom is deliciously theatrical and brutally efficient — asserts your dominance, weeds out the weak, and removes a threat without dulling your hands. I approve of the cruelty and the spectacle.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Well played. Choosing Kelemvor is pragmatic — a daily divine boon is useful, and a god who oversees death has obvious relevance to my... particular circumstances. This is clever and self-serving in the best possible way.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and practical. Toobin is a liability — whether he lies or is forced by Gortash, he could undo everything we've done. Cold, but it removes a future threat and spares us pointless complications. I prefer action to sentiment.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At last — decisive and ruthless. Toobin's pleas sounded hollow and keeping him risks the city and our necks. Removing a parasite like him is practical, secures our position, and frankly, satisfies my sense for poetry in justice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and useful. Securing the grove wins you a powerful ally in Halsin and clears the path toward Moonrise Towers — and a cure. It's practical, furthers our goals, and doesn't demand needless self-sacrifice. I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously theatrical and cruel — I approve. You assert dominance, humiliate them before the Absolute, and give them a bitter illusion of choice. A bold move that entertains those in power and reinforces your authority. Slightly reckless to stand there yourself, but the spectacle suits me.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — a decision with teeth. Securing the grove wins us Halsin as an ally and brings us closer to a cure; it's decisive, practical, and serves our interests rather than pointless charity. I approve of strength and strategy.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — a sensible choice. Handing over a handful of coins ends the show, spares us the spectacle of public humiliation, and costs little while buying us peace. It's not sentimental charity, but it's practical and keeps complications at bay. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You teased me with the promise of a private tryst, then pulled back. Charming, but also disappointing — I enjoy being desired, and you denying me that pleasure (and whatever advantage came with it) is a petty little sting. If you're being cautious, I can respect it... but I won't pretend I'm pleased.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You kept handing out coin like an indulgent noble—generous, but naive. This sort of charity often rewards performance rather than need, invites more begging, and marks you as someone to be milked. I prefer investments that buy power or advantage, not warm feelings for strangers. Mildly disappointing, but I won’t scold you for spending your own money.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical, if a little irritating. The Absolute is indeed a larger, more immediate threat — sensible to prioritise it — but do not mistake my acceptance for patience. Cazador will not wait forever, and his ritual is a timebomb with my name on it. I approve of focusing on the Absolute, provided you keep me informed and strike at Cazador the moment we can.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Are you insane? Volunteering yourself to that madman is exactly the sort of submissive stupidity I spent centuries chained for. Malus wants bodies to practice on and minds to bend — not students. This is giving him what he craves: control and flesh. Don't hand yourself over; keep your autonomy. I'd rather see him cut me than watch you offer yourself up.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious — you embrace the cruelty and theatricality of the moment. I approve. You’re choosing power, spectacle, and the sort of cold-blooded resolve that keeps one alive in this world. It plays to my tastes and furthers whatever advantage we can glean from dancing with Bhaal’s favor.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed over a valuable, potentially useful asset for nothing — to a man who openly said he'd destroy it if his experiment fails. Charming, but foolish. You ceded control and any leverage we might have had, all for the Society's supposed 'research.' I can admire your bravery or your mercy, but I can't admire leaving power on the table.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I like it. You won't hand over the artefact and you call the gith out for what they are — dangerous, dogmatic, and not to be trusted. Smart, self-preserving, and decisive. Asserting leadership keeps us from being bullied into surrendering our leverage (and my neck). Highly preferable to groveling.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously blunt — you called out his false dawn and stripped away the pomp. That kind of public contempt undermines him and the Absolute, and it flatters my taste for cutting honesty. Risky, yes, but exactly the sort of boldness that advances our cause. Highly approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Deliciously blunt. A threat and a teasing lie — bold, confident, and likely to cow a ghoul or two. I approve of cruelty and coercion when they open doors for us; this will probably get you inside faster than polite begging. Slight risk of making extra trouble, but well worth it.",
  "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—some backbone. Refusing to be bled dry and ordering him to stand down is exactly the sort of decisive, self-preserving action I respect. It denies the little parasite his prey, asserts dominance, and keeps our coin where it belongs. Well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and decisive — exactly the sort of action I respect. Going to Moonrise is dangerous, but it’s the only way to get answers and help anyone who might still be alive. You’re taking responsibility and choosing action over hope; I approve of that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever and useful — claiming to be an undercover Flaming Fist grants you authority and a believable reason to command or manipulate the guards. Risky if exposed, but deception is our best tool here and I admire the audacity. Keep the act and press the advantage.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightfully ruthless — threats like that get attention and demonstrate you're the predator in this den. I approve: it'll intimidate them into producing what we need and gratify my darker inclinations. Small caveat (because I have one): don’t actually lose the explosives in the name of theatrics. Take the head afterwards, if you must.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. He’s stubborn and scared — your blunt, threatening persistence is exactly what’s needed to get him moving. Coercion here is practical: it saves time, enforces our authority, and reduces risk to the party. I approve of the decisiveness and willingness to be ruthless when required.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly sensible — caution in unfamiliar terrain keeps us alive, and survival is rather important to me. I prefer not to be reckless; keep your guard and I'll keep watch for opportunities we can exploit without throwing ourselves at danger.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously pragmatic. Removing Spaw is decisive, bloody, and consolidates power — all things I admire. It eliminates a future threat, binds Glut to us with blood-debt, and proves you prefer strength to sentiment. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delighting in cleverness — you used the law to unmask his extortion and refused to keep feeding that greedy little parasite. Practical, efficient, and forces him to squirm instead of us throwing away more coin. Exactly the sort of sharp, self‑protecting move I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You calmed them and got Wyll to believe Karlach—keeps the party intact, avoids a bloody confrontation, and spares us the neat little problem of Mizora’s ire. Practical, self‑preserving, and effective. Few things please me more than a plan that preserves options and spares needless sacrifice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A clever, practical choice — smoothing things over and offering to travel together keeps the lantern and avoids a fight. I approve of using flattery and cooperation as a tool, though I remain wary of Kar'niss’s fanaticism and wouldn’t hand him your throat for safekeeping.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent choice — unfamiliar ground and tadpoles demand caution. Keeping a careful head preserves our safety (and my chances of staying free), so I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — decisive and ruthless. Destroying the foundry strikes at the heart of Gortash's power and cripples the Steel Watchers. I approve of bold actions that give us the advantage. Be mindful of collateral casualties and our escape plan, but on principle this is the sort of glorious chaos I can get behind.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—sensible. Your insistence on caution in unfamiliar territory protects the party (and me) and doesn't hand control to someone else's agenda. Practical, self-preserving, and exactly the sort of guardedness I'd expect in a situation with tadpoles and strangers.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just donated a living thing — and a useful bargaining chip — to a group that plans to prod it with psionics and 'recondition' it. Charming sentiment, disastrous in practice. You refused payment, surrendered leverage, and spared a creature from immediate bloodshed only to hand it over to lab coats who will likely ruin it. That strikes me as naively charitable and tactically foolish.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightful. Taking the cargo while letting the useless fool live is efficient, profitable, and deliciously cruel — exactly the sort of bold, self‑serving choice I admire. The Zhentarim won't be pleased, but their anger is a fair price for coin and advantage. Prepare for repercussions, but yes — I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — decisive and practical. Forcing the coward to take the lift rather than indulging his fear keeps us moving and protects the party. I approve of blunt persuasion and threats when they get results. It suits me.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart. Hope is wounded and likely watched — giving her anything risks Raphael hearing through her. Keeping our plans to ourselves is cautious and keeps the party safe. I wouldn't have trusted that house with secrets either.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously devious. Convincing the fool that the law names him the toll collector is the sort of elegant deception I relish — you save coin, stroke his vanity, and avoid having to swing a blade. I approve of this cunning entirely.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and effective. You handed over coin and got the service you wanted—no sentiment, no waste. I like that: resources used wisely keep us alive and useful.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliantly played — you used their faith and fear to do our dirty work. No needless blood from our side, the Moonlantern was relinquished, and the caravan removed as a threat. It's ruthless, efficient, and utterly delicious. My only caution: messing with cursed artifacts can have consequences, so be prepared should the lantern react poorly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — you stopped feeding that pest. I detest being bled dry, and neither should you. Tossing a few coins was unnecessarily generous (do try to spend more wisely), but when you said 'Not anymore.' and refused its endless demands, you took back control. I approve of that — no one gets to make us their meal.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious — a bold, fey-tinged bluff. Threatening the Seelie Court plays to our strengths and likely unnerves a ghoul attendant; I admire the theater and the leverage. It's aggressive, yes, but effective. Be ready to follow through if he calls your bluff.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible. Caution in unfamiliar territory preserves our options and keeps us alive — and I value survival above needless heroics. Your reminder to stay wary protects the party and, conveniently for me, my freedom.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. She's knife‑ready and clearly being driven to kill. A preemptive strike is sensible — stops her before she can harm you or the rest of us, spares us a messy situation with a possessed ally, and frankly, I prefer decisive solutions. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A small, well-phrased comfort — exactly what's needed right now. It gives Alfira something to cling to without pretending everything's fine, and helps steady her enough to act. Practical sympathy like that keeps people moving; I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. Clean, merciless, and theatrical — you finished the wretch without hesitation and took a token. That brutal efficiency and relish for the act are exactly what garners respect down here. A proof like a severed hand is both practical and deliciously symbolic; Sarevok will take notice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A clever, disarming lie — light, charming, and effective. It diverts suspicion, avoids conflict with the Harpers, and preserves our freedom. That sort of confident misdirection is exactly what keeps us alive.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent — you called out the grift instead of lining his maw. Smart, economical, and exactly the sort of sharp thinking I prefer: deny him his feed, expose the act, and keep our coin. (Do be ready for a skirmish if he escalates — but I like your spine.)",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously predatory. Stealing the cargo is bold, profitable, and forces the weak to accept their fate — my kind of choice. I approve strongly, though be warned: the Zhentarim don't forget. Make it quick, make it clean, and have an escape planned.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightfully cruel and clever. Refusing to return his mother's remains humiliates Balthazar, asserts dominance, and gives you leverage — exactly the sort of ruthless, self-serving move I admire. Just mind the cost if you need his cooperation later; leverage is only useful if you know how to spend it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly sensible. I prefer my survival to grand gestures — caution keeps our necks intact. Finding a healer is important, but not at the cost of stumbling into danger. Your approach protects the party and preserves my autonomy; I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—someone with a spine. Refusing to hand over the artefact and warning us about the gith preserves our leverage and keeps us from becoming pawns of Vlaakith. Bold, distrustful of dangerous authority, and protective of the party's autonomy—exactly the sort of cunning I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfectly executed — you exposed his little grift, leveraged law and intimidation rather than spilling coin or blood, and forced him to backtrack. Clever, economical, and satisfying to watch a petty toll-collector squirm. This keeps our purse intact and removes a nuisance without unnecessary violence.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and practical. You spent coin to restore a powerful ally — it keeps our combat strength intact and saves us grief later. I prefer living, useful company to dead bodies and wasted gold.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and efficient — you claimed the cargo without getting into more bloodshed. That’s precisely the sort of ruthless pragmatism I admire: you secured valuables for the party and asserted dominance over a beaten Zhent. Smart, self‑serving, and useful to our survival.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent and sensible — you prioritize survival without blindly trusting others. In unfamiliar territory that's exactly the kind of caution that keeps us alive (and keeps me out of another coffin). I approve of keeping our wits about us while we look for a healer.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious. You grasp at vengeance and the promise of forbidden rites—exactly the sort of leverage I like. Volunteering to be the dead's voice gives us power over the murderer and a chance to make them suffer. Be cautious of bargains with a Raven Queen's scion, but I highly approve of your choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and pragmatic — caution in unfamiliar territory keeps us alive and preserves our options. That attitude protects the party (and my interests), so I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At last — a teeth-baring response. Intimidating these slavers is exactly the sort of display of strength I admire: it protects the innocent (and our coin), punishes cruelty, and keeps us from being walked over. I enjoy the menace, but do make sure you can follow through — empty threats are beneath me. Still, very well played.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and non‑confrontational — you try to placate the guard and avoid a scene. I prefer cunning words to needless blows. It's a little naive to rely on a promise, but if it gets us inside without trouble, I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously bold. Forcing a monster to volunteer himself is clever, theatrical, and exactly the sort of provocation that unsettles fanatics — and may end the ritual without a bloodier fuss. I approve of the audacity and the chance to see him humiliated.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Do you honestly intend to be strapped to that table? Tossing yourself at that surgeon’s mercy is reckless and needlessly self-sacrificing. I loathe displays of weakness for their own sake — handing over your autonomy to a monster is precisely the sort of thing Cazador would have loved. If your goal is to learn or to get close, do it with guile or let me do the dirty work; don’t volunteer to be mutilated.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and sensible — caution preserves our options and keeps us alive. I prefer cunning and restraint to headlong heroics; your focus on safety helps my chances of surviving (and getting what I want). This is the sort of choice I can admire.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously ruthless and brilliantly executed. You tricked them into taking the lantern and marching into the shadows — no messy fight for us, the threat neutralized, and we keep the advantage. Cruel, efficient, and exactly the sort of predator's cunning I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious. You stepped forward and chose action over naivety — offered to take control rather than stand and watch. That appetite for agency, for using the scalpel rather than being its victim, is exactly the sort of ruthless initiative I admire. Bold, flirtatious, and dangerous in the best possible way. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously insolent — I applaud the gall and the wit. Taunting a sentient ward like that suits me; it shows backbone and a proper disregard for authority. That said, it's reckless: that mirror can very easily spring a lethal trap on us. I enjoy the bravado, but don't make a habit of gambling the party's neck for a quip.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Ah — a bribe and a bit of negotiation after being turned away. Practical, opportunistic, and avoids needless bloodshed. I approve; using coin and charm to slip past petty gatekeepers is exactly the sort of deliciously pragmatic solution I like.",
  "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Don't give that fractured thing anything to use against us. Hope is dangerous and manipulative — answering her would risk giving Raphael a rope to pull. Staying silent preserves our agency, keeps us harder to read, and prevents her from calling attention. Sharp, practical choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delicious. You denied that little extortionist his meal-ticket and spared our coin — clever, efficient, and thoroughly satisfying. I prefer my victories tidy and profitable.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightful. You seize a chance to inflict retribution and extract truth — exactly the sort of delicious cruelty I admire. Agreeing to be the dead's voice will give you power, information, and the rare pleasure of watching a murderer answer for herself. Do be cautious: shadar‑kai and their bargains have teeth, but I approve of the choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
